<TITLE> SC upholds ban on unauthorised student guides </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 9 (bdnews24.com)The Supreme Court has upheld a ban on publishing unauthorised notes and guide books for primary and secondary level students. The three member Appellate Division bench, headed by chief justice MM Ruhul Amin, quashed a petition against an earlier High Court order delivered on Mar 13, 2008. Abu Taher, president of Bangladesh Book Publishers and Sellers Association, filed the 'leave to appeal' petition against the High Court order. The government in December 2007 banned publishing, distribution and selling of notes and guide books that were not approved by the National Curriculum and Textbook Board. The High Court thereafter gave an order to district commissioners to take steps against publishing of the non-approved texts. Senior advocates Abdur Rob Chowdhury and Khandaker Mahbub Uddin Ahmad represented Taher in Wednesday's hearing. Attorney general Mahbubey Alam said after the verdict that the Appellate Division order restricted publishers from printing unofficial guide books. bd
